    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-10-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-10-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="586"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d586">
                <head>586. Letter From the Secretary of Defense (<persName corresp="#p_GTSJ1"
                        type="from">Gates</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                        State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d586fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 737.00/10–1460. Secret. A copy was sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_GBGAJ1">Goodpaster</persName>. Also published in part in <hi
                            rend="italic">Declassified Documents</hi>, 1981, 144B. In transmitting a
                        draft of this letter to <persName corresp="#p_GTSJ1">Gates</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_IJNII1">Irwin</persName> wrote in a covering
                        October 4 memorandum that it might not be desirable to suggest, as the Joint
                        Chiefs of Staff had recommended (see <ref target="#d584">Document
                        584</ref>), that “any doubt exists about the matter.” Rather than seek
                        Department of State concurrence for the Joint Chiefs’ proposals, <persName
                            corresp="#p_IJNII1">Irwin</persName> said it would be better for
                            <persName corresp="#p_GTSJ1">Gates</persName> to send the short letter
                        which <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_ISA1"
                            >ISA</gloss> had drafted. (Washington National Records Center, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 330, <gloss target="#t_OSD1"
                            >OSD</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_ISA1">ISA</gloss> Files: <gloss
                            target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 64 <gloss target="#t_A1">A</gloss> 2170,
                        092 Cuba)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-10-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 4, 1960</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Chris</persName>
                    </hi>: With respect to <persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>’s recent
                        statements<note n="2" xml:id="d586fn2">See <ref target="#d585fn2">footnote
                            2, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> indicating that the treaty under which we maintain the Base
                    at Guantanamo may be unilaterally denounced in the near future, I wanted you to
                    know that I have recently reaffirmed to the Joint Chiefs of Staff my
                    instructions that we hold this Base against all forms of harassment, including
                    armed attack. Although we anticipate taking no provocative steps, contingency
                    plans have been prepared under the direction of the Joint Chiefs of Staff to
                    include defensive actions beyond the perimeter of the Base should this be
                    required to meet armed attack.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GTSJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Thomas S. Gates</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
